d their co-authors have written accounts of how humans and animals interact in labs, in farms, in zoos, and in African forests, among other places. Modeled after the classic A World of Babies, an edited collection of imagined Dr. Spock manuals from around the world—With Animals focuses on human-animal relationships in their myriad forms.This is ethnographic fiction for those curious about how animals are used for a variety of different tasks around the world. To be sure, animal guides are not a universal genre, so Living with Animals offers an imaginative solution, doing justice to the ways details about animals are conveyed in culturally specific ways by adopting a range of voices and perspectives. How we capitalize on animals, how we live with them, and how humans attempt to control the untamable nature around them are all considered by the authors of this wild read.If you have ever experienced a moment of "what if" curiosity—what is it like to be a gorilla in a zoo, to work in a pig factory farm, to breed cows and horses, this book is for you. A light-handed and light-hearted approach to a fascinating and nuanced subject, Living with Animals suggests many ways in which we can and do coexist with our non-human partners on Earth.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aAnimals and civilization. 0aHuman-animal relationships. 4aAnthropology. 4aGeneral Science. 4aNature Guides & Natural History. 7aNATURE / Animal Rights.2bisacsh1 aAltfeld, Heather, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaynes-Rock, Marcus, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlanchette, Alex, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBolten, Catherine E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCalvert, Scout, econtributor.4ctb4https